A vintage-style illustration of an intricate mechanical calendar mechanism built from brass gears, cogs, and spinning wheels, viewed from above like a clockmaker's workbench. Multiple calendar pages with grid patterns float and interlock with the machinery. Copper pipes connect different sections like a steam-powered system. The scene is bathed in warm amber light from an old desk lamp casting dramatic shadows. Scattered around are tiny tools, screws, and technical blueprints with abstract diagrams. The aesthetic combines Victorian-era engineering drawings with functional computing machinery, suggesting the complex interconnected systems beneath simple calendar interfaces. Muted sepia tones with occasional pops of deep teal and rust orange. Textured paper background with subtle aging and coffee stains at the edges.
